content.protection: Can place smaller nuts and a .75 cam if you are leading. You can also set an anchor up from the top so you can do it on top rope.
content.location: Far left of Cyclops Eye. There is a small tree at the base of this climb.

content.description: Crux after exiting the pod. Fists and OW moves to good holds near the top.
content.protection: Med-Large Gear   Anchor must be extend from the edge to due large loose blocks
content.location: North Side wall at Upper Sullivan's Canyon, just East of the Lieback Crack (but on the opposite side of the canyon).

content.description:
This follows the crack, right of cyclops eye, and in the left side of a wide stem box.  The climb is very slick off the start with a finger crack that opens as it gets higher.  

 The oringal rating, as listed in Prescott Climbing Guide, is 10a.  While I wanted to honor those who climbed here originally I’ve left that rating.  However I think this one falls much closer to 10+.... maybe 11-.  Get ready, you’re in for a fight.
Climb up a blocky start to a ledge about 15ft up.  The follow the obvious hands/ thin hands (relative of course) to the top.  Long slings or static line is needed to set up a top rop.
content.location: The crack located left of the cyclops eye.

content.description: Protecting the move before pulling into the pod, can be tricky. After the pod it gets progressively easier following the crack.
content.protection:
micro to medium sized gear.

 -The climbs to the left and right I believe are .10's...they are in the guidebook
content.location: Across the canyon from twin and S crack. Gear anchor or top out and rap back down.

content.description: Hardest move at the bottom. Getting established in the crack with slick feet and finger locks. Another hard section just before the top when the climb gets steep again.
content.protection: Small to Medium Cams. Top anchor will need to be extended away from the edge due to loose blocks.
content.location: North Side wall at Upper Sullivan's Canyon, just East of the Lieback Crack (but on the opposite side of the canyon).
